Craig,

You have a point.  It looks like the parameterized runner could use a
@BeforeParameter / @AfterParameter hook.  If that would be useful,
could you open a Feature Request on SourceForge?  Thanks,

   David Saff

On 3/22/07, cwhite102 &lt;craig.whitex@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; Thank you all for the suggestions.  I&#39;m just getting back on this
&gt; now after being pulled to higher priority things.  What could be
&gt; higher priority than unit tests!?
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;ve checked out the Parameterized test runner.  Nice addition and I
&gt; can make it work this way.  However, one thing I&#39;m not happy with is
&gt; that it is the &#39;cross product&#39; of the Test methods and parameters.
&gt; Thus I can&#39;t have a bunch of test methods for a single parameterized
&gt; instance.  It&#39;s sortof missing the &#39;before&#39;/&#39;after&#39; hooks needed to
&gt; set it up the way I&#39;d like -  Configure, Test A, Test B,...,
&gt; Shutdown.  The &#39;BeforeClass&#39;/&#39;AfterClass&#39; hooks don&#39;t work either as
&gt; they are only called once in total.
&gt;
&gt; I sortof expected it to instantiate the class and then run all the
&gt; test methods (seeing how it was on the constructor).  But it doesn&#39;t
&gt; work this way.
&gt;
&gt; Craig
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; --- In junit@yahoogroups.com, &quot;hurne_jim&quot; &lt;hurne_jim@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; JUnit 4 actually has a Parameterized custom test runner that allows
&gt; &gt; you to run the same test(s) with different parameters.  Take a
&gt; look at
&gt; &gt; org.junit.runners.Parameterized in the JUnit Javadoc.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I&#39;ve been working on an &quot;XML&quot; version of Parameterized that allows
&gt; you
&gt; &gt; to store your test parameters in an XML file.  It&#39;s part of the
&gt; &gt; JunitExt project (http://www.junitext.org).  I must warn you that
&gt; it&#39;s
&gt; &gt; still in the early stages of development.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; However, it sounds like using Parameterized might be easier than my
&gt; &gt; XMLParameterizedRunner, as you&#39;ll likely need to do something
&gt; &gt; programatically with Hibernate.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; The nice thing about custom test runners is that they work with
&gt; IDEs.
&gt; &gt;  For example, you can use Parameterized and still be able to run
&gt; the
&gt; &gt; tests from within Eclipse.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; -Jim Hurne
